 and a conceptual base needed to construct an understanding of the world. The contributors address identification of deafblindness, planning and intervention, development, family support, and education.Just as McInnes and Treffry's "Deafblind Infants and Children" helped to change the approach to and the perception of deafblind children, this collection will assist in fostering a new approach to the education of and support for older children, youth and adults who are deafblind. An essential part of this process is to set forth standards for program development, implementation, and evaluation, which this volume aims to accomplish. It will make an essential contribution to the expanding field of services for the deafblind population of all ages, and to the improved understanding of parents, family members, and professionals who support them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aDeafblind people. 4aDISCOUNT-B. 7aEDUCATION / Special Education / Physical Disabilities.2bisacsh1 aBridgett, Gary, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Norman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCampbell, Susan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Rodney, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCloke, Gini, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDemerling, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEisler, Sheila, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeenens, Douglas L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMamer, Linda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatthews, Malcolm, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGlinchey, Janis